cs.DM, cs.DS, cs.GT, cs.CG, cs.LG. 

The paper deals with graph classes and their structural properties, as well as algorithmic consequences. This suggests that it could belong to several sub-categories, including Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM), Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS), Graph Theory (cs.GT), Computational Geometry (cs.CG), and Logic in Computer Science (cs.LG). However, since the focus is primarily on graph classes and their properties, cs.DM and cs.GT are the most likely categories. The use of width parameters and algorithmic consequences also suggests cs.DS as a possible category. The mention of induced minors and subgraphs suggests cs.CG as a possible category. Finally, the mention of modelling power and the use of width parameters suggests cs.LG as a possible category.
